	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hey,
<br />
<br /> I was wondering if anyone has the pinout for the SNES Justifier gun? I need to know the connections at the PCB inside the gun. I'm looking to find out as I plan on re-wiring one to use on the Yobo FC3. 
<br />
<br />Cheers

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Thu Dec 24, 2009 10:42 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />From the square end to the round end, the pinout for anything that plugs into a Super NES controller port is power, clock, strobe, data, data 2, data 3, ground. Data 3 is bidirectional; <a href="http://snesemu.black-ship.net/misc/techdocs/snestech.txt" class="postlink">this page</a> seems to indicate that the Super Scope and Justifier work by sending a pulse on data 3 when the CRT beam crosses the detector, causing PPU2 to latch the raster position just like on the Super Scope. So it might not be much more than a Zapper; if so, the trigger should show up on data or data 2. But you might want to read an existing Super NES emulator's input handling source code to make sure.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


